\end{figure}

The experimental design involves a superconducting sample placed in a cryostat, which is cooled to below its critical temperature using a liquid helium bath. A magnetic field will be applied to the sample using electromagnets, and the field strength will be varied using a control system. The magnetic field will be maintained at a distance from the sample to avoid the Meissner effect.

The sample will be made of a high-temperature superconductor, such as YBa$_2$Cu$_3$O$_{7-\delta}$. The specifications of the superconducting material will be optimized to maximize the quantum flux pinning effect.

The quantum flux lines will be detected and measured using a scanning SQUID microscope. This technique involves placing a superconducting quantum interference device (SQUID) near the sample and measuring the change in the phase of the supercurrent as it passes through the SQUID.

