The experimental results will provide valuable insights into the quantum flux pinning phenomenon in high-temperature superconductors. The simulated data suggest that the flux pinning strength increases with both the magnetic field and temperature. The expected variation of flux pinning strength with temperature, as shown in Figure \ref{fig:flux\_pinning\_temp}, indicates a non-linear relationship, which may validate or challenge the theoretical framework laid out in the previous sections.

\section{Conclusion}

This study has presented a comprehensive theoretical framework and experimental design for investigating quantum flux pinning in high-temperature superconductors. The experimental setup involves cooling the sample to below its critical temperature, applying a magnetic field, and detecting and measuring the quantum flux lines using a scanning SQUID microscope. The expected results will provide insights into the potential impact on energy transmission technology. The outcomes may validate or challenge the theoretical framework, leading to further research in this field.


